&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Here&#39;s a possible solution using **.join()**.

&gt; The array.join() method is an inbuilt function in JavaScript which is
&gt; used to join the elements of an array into a string.The elements of
&gt; the string will be separated by a specified separator and its default
&gt; value is comma(, ).

Note that by passing the empty string to join you can get the concatenation of all elements of the array.  

In other words **join(&#39;&#39;)** will also remove the extra commas.

The final result of this process is then converted to a number using parseInt, I think this is an easy solution to understand for beginners.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;


&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    // Expected result is an array like this
    // var newArray = [123];
    var array = [1,2,3];
    var newArray = [parseInt(array.join(&#39;&#39;))];
    console.log(newArray);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

**Bonus**  
I see that many users here suggested the unary operator + instead of parseInt.

There is an interesting answer and discussion on the topic [here on Stackoverflow][1].


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17106681/parseint-vs-unary-plus-when-to-use-which

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let array = [1,2,3];
    let number = Number.parseInt(array.join(&#39;&#39;));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

&gt; Explanation:

`join(&#39;&#39;)` will concatenate all the elements in an array into a string.  
`+` will convert it into a number.
  

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let array = [1, 2, 3];
    console.log([+array.join(&#39;&#39;)]);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You could reduce the array.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    var array = [1, 2, 3],
        result = array.reduce(([a], b) =&gt; [(a || 0) * 10 + b], []);

    console.log(result);
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

A shorter one as proposed by T. J. Crowder in the comments.


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    var array = [1, 2, 3],
        result = [array.reduce((a, b) =&gt; a * 10 + b, 0)];

    console.log(result);
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can join it like this

